154":"about 1154","1207":"1207","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bruce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a place in Normandy, probably from Brix (La Manche).","Altered form of French   Brousse  .","History: The son of the Domesday baron, a friend of David I of Scotland, was granted by him the Lordship of Annandale in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Brousse","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: topographic name for someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Brewis","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."]}]},{"name":"Euphemia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a Late Greek name derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>phēnai</i> ‘to speak’. This was the name of various early saints, notably a virgin martyr said to have been burned at the stake at Chalcedon in  307 . It had a limited popularity in some regions in the 16th and 17th centuries and returned to favour in the Victorian period, especially in the pet form   Effie .  It is little used at present."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Euphemia de Bruce was born about 1153, in Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland, her father, Sir Robert De Bruce 2nd Lord of Annandale, was 58 and her mother, Euphemia d'Aumale, was 25. She had at least 1 son with Ivon Kirkpatrick of Closeburn. She died in 1179, in her hometown, at the age of 27."},"et":{"Abt 1153–1179":"umbes 1153–1179","1142–1245":"1142–1245","1153–1179":"1153–1179","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1156–1191":"1156–1191","1158–1212":"1158–1212","–1192":"–1192","1128–1150":"1128–1150","1146–1207":"1146–1207","1096–1143":"1096–1143","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1192":"1192","1191":"1191","Abt 1153":"umbes 1153","1128":"1128","1158":"1158","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1245":"1245","1156":"1156","1155":"1155","about 1154":"umbes 1154","1207":"1207","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1153–1179":"noin 1153–1179","1142–1245":"1142–1245","1153–1179":"115